@NODE "introduction" "InstallerGen - Introduction"

InstallerGen - Introduction

Amiga OS includes a standard utility which can be used for installing software. It interprets scripts which can be written in a standard text editor and can be used for copying files, checking versions, creating drawers and other operations related to software installation.

The scripting language is similar to LISP and is reasonably well documented in the freely available Installer distribution. See Installer43.3 on Aminet for details.

While the language is easy to understand and develop, it's not particularly fun to work with, and can sometimes be quite monotonous to create the scripts you require. Because of this, applications are often released without installer scripts, sometimes requiring the user to copy files to different locations by hand. Obviously this isn't ideal, but sometimes a coder's time would be better spent on other projects than writing boring installer scripts...

So InstallerGen was born! I started writing it in 2011 in order to create scripts for my own software releases, and soon found that it is something that a lot of other developers would appreciate too. I neglected the project for a couple of years but decided to finally finish it and release it.

InstallerGen allows you to create installer scripts using many of the key features of the Installer utility without writing a single line of code. Some more advanced features may require additional coding, but InstallerGen can to a lot of the legwork for you here too.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "disclaimer" "InstallerGen - Disclaimer"

InstallerGen - Disclaimer

Okay, you know the drill... While I have tried to ensure this software won't cause any harm to anyone's system, I can't guarantee it, and I can't be held responsible for any loss or damage caused by the use of this software. There are so many different computer configurations out there, and I only have a couple of combinations that I can test, so all I can say is, "It Works on My Machine" :)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "operation" "InstallerGen - How It Works"

InstallerGen - How It Works

InstallerGen works by allowing you to create a list of the steps you would like the installer script to take. Each step represents one of the main Installer utility functions and can be customised as required.

Once the steps are all in place, the script is generated and saved to your computer, where you can test it, tweak it as necessary and finally include it in your package for distribution.

Projects can be saved for future modification and use.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "requirements" "InstallerGen - Requirements"

InstallerGen Requirements

InstallerGen has some minimum requirements which you should really have sorted out before running the application.

 - AmigaOS 3.x or compatible
 - MUI
 - NList.mcc

InstallerGen has been tested on OS3.9, OS4.1 and MorphOS 3.3, and has been reported as working on Aros Vision (68k)

I can't guarantee it will work on all configurations and all OSes however. If you find it doesn't work on your setup, please let me know!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "installation" "InstallerGen - Installation"

Installing InstallerGen

InstallerGen does not require any special installation steps. You can copy the complete drawer wherever you like and it should work from there. There is also an installation script which will do this for you, but that's mainly there as an example of what InstallerGen can do! 

To upgrade InstallerGen, simply copy it over the previous version.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "usage" "InstallerGen - Usage"

Using InstallerGen

InstallerGen can be started by double-clicking on its icon. When it starts you'll be shown the main window which is where you will build your installer scripts.

Starting InstallerGen from the shell with the argument "debug" will produce some debug output which might be useful to you, but mainly to me, in finding problems.

More detail on the usage can be found by following the links below.

   @{" Main Window      " Link "mainwindow"}  The main window

   @{" Program Menus    " Link "menus"}  The menus of the main InstallerGen window

   @{" Properties Tab   " Link "properties"}  The Script Properties tab in the main window

   @{" Step Types       " Link "steptypes"}  A list of the step types available and their functions

   @{" Options Window   " Link "optionswindow"}  A list of the options chosen for file copying or multiple choice steps

   @{" Variables Window " Link "varswindow"}  A list of the variables used in the script

   @{" Warnings Window  " Link "warningswindow"}  A list of the warnings from the last script generation

   @{" Example Project  " Link "example"}  A brief explanation of the example project included

@ENDNODE

@NODE "mainwindow" "InstallerGen - Main Window"

The InstallerGen Main Window

The main window is where you build your installer script. Here you will find a list of the steps you wish your script to carry out, and the controls specific to those steps. There is also a second tab containing the properties of the overall script.

Please note that some of the controls are renamed depending on the context of the current step.

Details on these controls are as follows:

   @{b}- Script Steps@{ub}
This listview lists all the steps in the current project. It lists them in the order they will be executed by the Installer utility, and is reflected by the step number in the first column. The Step Type shows the type of action to be performed, and the Comment is an internal comment added by you that will not be shown to the end user, but will be included in the script as a comment. This can help you identify steps later on.

   @{b}- Add / Delete / Move up / Move down@{ub}
These gadgets control the main list of steps, allowing you to add new steps, and delete or move up or down existing steps.

   @{b}- Step Controls@{ub}
This pane lets you edit the details of the currently selected step. The exact options present will depend on the type of step chosen, so not all of the options below will be available at all times.

   @{b}- Step Type@{ub}
This cycle gadget sets the type of step that is currently selected in the list. For a full explanation of the step types @{"click here" LINK "steptypes"}.

   @{b}- Step Comment@{ub}
This is a hidden comment which is not shown to the end user when running your script, but is shown in the steps list and is included as a comment in the script itself.

   @{b}- % Complete@{ub}
If a value other than 0 is entered here, this value will be shown by the installer utility as the % completed during the execution of the step.

   @{b}- Message Text@{ub}
This text is shown whenever the current step is executed. Use \n to enter a new line.

   @{b}- Comment Text@{ub}
This text is inseted as an additional, highlighted comment in the finished script. It will not be shown to the end user unless they open the script in a text editor

   @{b}- Create drawer automatically@{ub}
Enabling this checkbox will cause the current step to create a drawer when executed. The "Content / Default" text gadget is used to provide the drawer's name.

   @{b}- Variable Name / Result Variable@{ub}
Enter the name of the variable this step will store its result in, or otherwise use. For example, enter @default-dest to store the selected path in the default destination variable. @{"Read more about variables" LINK "variables"}.

   @{b}- ? Gadget@{ub}
The ? gadget will open the variables list, showing you which variables are already available for your script. @{"Read more about the variables window" LINK "varswindow"}.

   @{b}- Condition@{ub}
These gadgets are used for setting the condition for an If statement. The cycle gadget is used to select a comparison type, and the text gadget contains the value to compare the variable named in Variable Name to.

   @{b}- Contents / Default String@{ub}
This text box is used for setting the default setting or value of the step, such as the default name of the drawer to create.

   @{b}- Help Text@{ub}
The text to appear when the help button is pressed in the installer utility. If it's left blank, the standard help text for that step type is used instead.

   @{b}- Link to previous 'If' statement@{ub}
If this box is checked, the step is only executed if the previous if statement is true. @{"Read more about If statements" LINK "ifstep"}.

   @{b}- Create / copy / delete icons automatically@{ub}
If this box is checked, any files or drawers created, copied or deleted in the current step will also have the same action carried out on their icon file. No error will be generated if an associated icon file doesn't exist.

   @{b}- Force Confirmation@{ub}
This cycle gadget sets at which user level the script should be paused to get confirmation from the user. The default is "Off" which is standard behaviour. Note that only Message step types can be forced to display for all user levels.

   @{b}- Open List...@{ub}
Clicking this gadget opens the list of options or files associated with the current step. @{"Read more about the options window" LINK "optionswindow"}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "menus" "InstallerGen - Program Menus"

InstallerGen Program Menus

The main window uses some menus for controlling InstallerGen. Three main menus are provided - Project, Edit and Script. The menu items function as follows:

   @{b}- Project->Load...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga L)
Opens afile requester allowing the user to select an InstallerGen project to load.

   @{b}- Project->Save@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga S)
Saves the current project. If a filename hasn't been selected previously, a file requester will be opened to allow the user to choose the file to save.

   @{b}- Project->Save As...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga A)
Opens a file requester to select the file to save the current project as.

   @{b}- Project->About...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga ?)
Shows an About requester containing version information.

   @{b}- Project->Quit@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga Q)
Quits InstallerGen.

   @{b}- Edit->New step@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga N)
Creates a new step in the main steps list. The same as clicking the Add gadget.

   @{b}- Edit->Copy step@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga P)
Duplicates the currently selected step.

   @{b}- Edit->Delete step@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga K)
Deletes the currently selected step. The same as clicking the Delete gadget.

   @{b}- Script->Generate...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga G)
Opens a file requester for the user to select the installer script to create, and writes all the steps in the list to that script.

   @{b}- Script->Show Warnings...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga W)
Opens the Waenings window which lists any the warnings generated during the last script generation run.

   @{b}- Script->Show Variables...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga R)
Removes the selected mount from the Saved Mounts list. Equivalent to the Remove button. Will not remove the mount from the Active Mounts list if it is already active.

   @{b}- Script->Autospread Complete Percentages@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga %)
Spreads out the completed percentage values so that each step is an equal percentage level above the previous step. This gives 100% for the last step and 0% for the start, with the rest of the steps in between spread evenly.

   @{b}- Settings->Create Project Icons@{ub}
When this item is checked, InstallerGen will create a project icon whenever it saves a project. If an icon already exists, it will not overwrite the icon. This makes sure any custom icon settings you may have are not lost. Default is checked.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "properties" "InstallerGen - Properties Tab"

InstallerGen - Properties Tab

The Script Properties tab allows the user to set the overall properties of the script. The options currently available are:

   @{b}- Script / Application Name@{ub}
The name of the application, package or files that the script is installing. This will be shown in the default welcome message, and cannot be left blank. This name will also be set in the install script's icon tooltypes.

   @{b}- Script Comment@{ub}
This comment is inserted as a comment at the top of the finished installer script. The end user won't be shown this message during installation but it will be visible if you open the script in a text editor.

   @{b}- Script Version@{ub}
A version number and other details can be inserted here. They will be included as a comment in the finished script and will take the standard Amiga version string format so that the script can be queried with the version command or the icon info window.

   @{b}- Script Filename@{ub}
The filename of the finished script. This will be set to the filename chosen when the script is generated.

   @{b}- Script Working Directory@{ub}
This is the root directory @{i}on your local computer@{ui}, and is the path that the is used as a start point for files installed to a relative path. For example, if you want to install all the files in Work:Programming/Projects/MyGame/ you should set this as the working directory. Any files added to the script will relative to this drawer, and the directory structure from this point on will be recreated at the destination during installation.

   @{b}- Default Install Destination@{ub}
This is the default installation destination directory on the end user's machine. It is where the files will be copied to unless a "Choose Location" step is used in the script to save a path to the @default-dest variable. This path will be the default choice on the select destination step during installation.

   @{b}- Script Icon@{ub}
An icon can be chosen for the install script with this cycle gadget. If set to "None", no icon will be added to the script. You should add your own icon in this case as installer scripts require an icon. However, if you have a custom icon, set this to "None" to prevent InstallerGen overwriting your icon. Also, if "None" is selected, the tooltypes for app name, minimum user level and default user level will not be set.
You can choose from OS3.0/3.1, OS3.5/3.9, OS4 or MorphOS icons.

   @{b}- Minimum User Level@{ub}
This cycle gadget sets the minimum user level that it's possible to select when starting the installation. In most cases, this should be left as "Novice". @{b}Note:@{ub} This setting is stored in the install script's tooltype, so if no icon is selected this setting will have no effect.

   @{b}- Default User Level@{ub}
This cycle gadget sets the default user level selected when starting the installation. @{b}Note:@{ub} This setting is stored in the install script's tooltype, so if no icon is selected this setting will have no effect.

   @{b}- Generate Script@{ub}
Clicking this gadget opens a file requester where you can select a name for the script to create. Once selected, the script will be generated. Any errors or warnings that occur during this time will be shown in the @{"Warnings window" LINK "warningswindow"}.
@{b}Note:@{ub} Be careful not to overwrite the project file with the script - you cannot recover the project from the generated script.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "steptypes" "InstallerGen - Step Type"

InstallerGen Step Types

InstallerGen supports a number of step types which correspond to many of the main Installer utility commands. The step types currently supported are shown below:

   @{" Message                       " LINK "messagestep"}  Message for the user

   @{" Choose Location               " LINK "locationstep"}  Choose an installation location

   @{" Radio Buttons                 " LINK "radiostep"}  Give the user a list of options to pick one from

   @{" Checkboxes                    " LINK "checkboxstep"}  Give the user a list of options to pick any number from

   @{" Enter String                  " LINK "stringstep"}  Allows user to enter a string

   @{" Copy Files                    " LINK "copyfilesstep"}  Copies one or more files to a location

   @{" Copy Files with Version Check " LINK "copycheckstep"}  Copies one or more files with version checking

   @{" Comment                       " LINK "commentstep"}  Inserts a comment into the finished script

   @{" Create Drawer                 " LINK "drawerstep"}  Creates a drawer

   @{" If                            " LINK "ifstep"}  Starts an If comparison sequence

   @{" Else                          " LINK "elsestep"}  Adds an Else step to an If statement

   @{" Welcome                       " LINK "Welcomestep"}  Replaces the standard welcome step with a custom message

   @{" User-Startup Assign           " LINK "userstartupassignstep"}  Adds an assign to the S:User-Startup file

   @{" User-Startup Command          " LINK "userstartupcommandstep"}  Adds an AmigaDOS command to the S:User-Startup file

   @{" Run Command                   " LINK "runcommandstep"}  Executes an AmigaDOS command

   @{" Rename                        " LINK "renamestep"}  Rename a file or drawer

   @{" Delete                        " LINK "deletestep"}  Delete a file or drawer

   @{" Assign                        " LINK "assignstep"}  Creates an assign right away

   @{" Set Variable                  " LINK "setvariablestep"}  Sets the contents of a variable

   @{" Concatenate Strings           " LINK "catstep"}  Joins two strings together

   @{" Installer Command             " LINK "installercommandstep"}  Adds an Installer utility command to the script

   @{" Get Version                   " LINK "catstep"}  Gets the version details of a given file

   @{" Check Exists                  " LINK "catstep"}  Checks if a given file or directory exists

   @{" Exit                          " LINK "exitstep"}  Forces the Installer utility to stop running the script and exit

@ENDNODE
@NODE "messagestep" "InstallerGen - Message Step Type"

Message Step Type

This step presents the user with a message in the Installer utility window and waits for them to confirm before carrying on.

The Message Text field contains the information that will be displayed. Use \n to enter a newline.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "locationstep" "InstallerGen - Choose Location Step Type"

Choose Location Step Type

This step presents the user with a screen for selecting a destination for installation. A message can be provided as a prompt in the Message Text field.

A drawer can optionally be created automatically for the user. The user will be informed whether a drawer will be created or not.

The Variable Name field contains the name of the variable the resulting path is stored in. Normally this would be @default-dest, but can be something else depending on your requirements. To read more about variables {"click here" LINK "variables"}.

The Content / Default field is used to enter the name of the drawer that is to be created.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "radiostep" "InstallerGen - Radio Buttons Step Type"

Radio Buttons Step Type

This step type gives the user multiple options to choose from, of which only one can be selected. A prompt message can be entered in the Message Text box.

Click the Open List... button to open the {"Options Window" LINK "optionswindow"} where you can choose what options to give the user. A separate variable name is added for each option. The selected variable will be set to 1 and all the others to 0 after the user has made their choice.

Additionally, a variable name is given in the main step controls. This variable contains a number corresponding to the selected option - 0 for the first option, 1 for the second and so on. @{b}Please note:@{ub} The official Installer utility documentation describes this function as storing the result as a bitmask. This is only true for the checkboxes and not for the radio buttons!

The default selected option is chosen by enabling the Active Entry checkbox for the desired item in the Options window.

A maximum of 32 options are permitted.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "checkboxstep" "InstallerGen - Checkbox Step Type"

Checkbox Step Type

This step type gives the user multiple options to choose from, of which the user can select as many as they want. A prompt message can be entered in the Message Text box.

Click the Open List... button to open the {"Options Window" LINK "optionswindow"} where you can choose what options to give the user. A separate variable name is added for each option. The variables for each selected option will be set to 1 and the others to 0 after the user has made their choices.

Additionally, a variable name is given in the main step controls. This variable contains a bitmask of the selected options - the first bit corresponds to the first option, the second bit to the second option and so on.

The default selected options are chosen by enabling the Active Entry checkbox for each desired item in the Options window.

A maximum of 32 options are permitted.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "stringstep" "InstallerGen - Enter String Step Type"

Enter String Step Type

This step type gives the user the ability to enter a string. A prompt can be provided in the Message Text field.

The string entered by the user is stored in the variable entered in the Variable Name field. @{"See here" LINK "variables"} to read more about variables.

The Content / Default field can be used to set the default contents of the string.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "copyfilesstep" "InstallerGen - Copy Files Step Type"

Copy Files Step Type

This step type copies the files listed in the Options window. A prompt can be supplied in the Message text field.

Click the Open List... gadget to open the @{"Options window" LINK "optionswindow"}. Here you can select files to be copied. Click Add to add multiple files, or click Add Drawers... to select entire drawers to be copied. These file requesters will open in the Script Working Directory as selected in the @{"Script Properties" LINK "properties"} tab. Paths selected are relative to this location unless you use the file requester to choose a volume, in which case the paths are absolute.

To copy the files to an absolute location, the Destination and Filename fields can be manually edited afterwards. This should be used to install files to LIBS: for example.

Create / copy icons automatically can be selected if desired. If this is selected, any .info files corresponding to selected files will be copied alongside the selected files.

A maximum of 100 files or drawers are permitted.

Please note that the files copied with this step are not checked for version information so there is a chance files could be replaced with older versions. To copy with version checking, see the @{"Copy Files with Version Check" LINK "copycheckstep"}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "copycheckstep" "InstallerGen - Copy Files with Version Check Step Type"

Copy Files with Version Check Step Type

This step type copies the files listed in the Options window. A prompt can be supplied in the Message text field, but the Installer utility will normally show the filename being copied.

Unlike the basic @{"Copy Files step type" LINK "copysteptype"}, this step type checks the version information for the files being copied and will not copy older versions over newer versions, or will prompt the user depending on the user experience level selected at the start of installation. Please note that the file will not be copied if it has the same version information as an identically-named file already at the destination. User confirmation will be requested for each file.

Click the Open List... gadget to open the @{"Options window" LINK "optionswindow"}. Here you can select files to be copied. Click Add to add multiple files, or click Add Drawers... to select entire drawers to be copied. These file requesters will open in the Script Working Directory as selected in the @{"Script Properties" LINK "properties"} tab. Paths selected are relative to this location unless you use the file requester to choose a volume, in which case the paths are absolute.

To copy the files to an absolute location, the Destination and Filename fields can be manually edited afterwards. This should be used to install files to LIBS: for example.

Create / copy icons automatically can be selected if desired. If this is selected, any .info files corresponding to selected files will be copied alongside the selected files.

A maximum of 100 files or drawers are permitted.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "commentstep" "InstallerGen - Comment Step Type"

Comment Step Type

This comment simply inserts a comment into the finished script. The end user will not see this unless they open the install script in a text viewer.

Message Text contains the actual text to be inserted into the script.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "drawerstep" "InstallerGen - Create Drawer Step Type"

Create Drawer Step Type

This step creates a drawer on the user's computer. A prompt can be provided in the Message Text field.

The Content / Default field is used to set the name of the drawer. This is relative to the installation location.

The Create / copy icons automatically check box can be enabled to create a standard icon for the newly created drawer.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "ifstep" "InstallerGen - If Step Type"

If Step Type

The If step type is used to make a decision based on variables used in the script. The step starts a sequence that subsequent steps can be added to by enabling their "Link to previous 'If' statement" checkboxes.

All following the If statement with this checkbox enabled will only be executed if the If statement comparison is found to be true. The first step with the "Link to previous 'If' statement" checkbox unchecked ends the sequence and returns the script to executing every step.

A prompt can be provided in the Message text drawer.

The Variable Name field contains the variable name to be checked.

The condition cycle gadget can be used to choose any standard comparison type, and the text box is used to enter what the variable is to be compared to. This can be a value, a string or another variable. Be sure to use quotes around any string used here, e.g. "Yes", otherwise the Installer utility will try to interpret it as a variable name.

@{b}Note:@{ub} Not all versions of the Installer utility will execute the If sections of the script where it finds them. Some versions (e.g. InstallerNG and the MorphOS version) save these steps until the end in order to support a "Back" function, so be aware that your If... Else blocks may be executed after the steps following it.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "elsestep" "InstallerGen - Else Step Type"

Else Step Type

This step causes the @{"If statement" LINK "ifstep"} it is linked to, to be reversed for the following linked steps. So, any steps following the Else statement which are linked to the previous If statement will only be executed if that If statement was found to be false.

As with the If statement, the first step following the Else statement which isn't linked to the previous If statement will finish the sequence and will be executed regardless.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "welcomestep" "InstallerGen - Welcome Step Type"

Welcome Step Type

If this step is included in the script, it overrides the default welcome message and replaces it with the message provided in the Message Text field.

This step will also only produce the welcome message when it is executed, so some steps can be executed before it is shown to the user.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "userstartupassignstep" "InstallerGen - User-Startup Assign Step Type"

User-Startup Assign Step Type

This step type is used to insert an assign command into the S:User-Startup file. A prompt can be provided using the Message Text field.

The Assign Name field contains the name of the assign to create, for example MyProg:. Please ensure to include the trailing semicolon!

The Assign Destination field contains the directory the assign will point to. This will normally be a variable such as @default-dest, but can be a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "SYS:MyDir".

@ENDNODE
@NODE "userstartupcommandstep" "InstallerGen - User-Startup Command Step Type"

User-Startup Command Step Type

This step type is used to insert an AmigaDOS command into the S:User-Startup file. A prompt can be provided using the Message Text field. If an assign is required in the User-Startup, the @{"User-Startup Assign Step" LINK "userstartupassignstep"} can be used instead.

The Command field contains the full command to insert. A variable can be used here or a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "SetEnv MyEnvVar 1".

Please note that to include a variable as part of the command, you need to enter a Cat statement, for example:

  (cat "SetEnv MyAppEnv " #MyStringVar)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "runcommandstep" "InstallerGen - Run Command Step Type"

Run Command Step Type

This step allows an AmigaDOS command to be executed directly from the installer script. This can be useful to run a command to initialise settings for example, or running the FixFonts command etc.

The Command field contains the full command to insert. A variable can be used here or a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "SetEnv MyEnvVar 1".

There are a couple of things to note about running AmigaDOS commands from the Installer Utility like this. First off, arguments must be passed as separate strings. For example, to open a guide, you should do something like:

  "Sys:Utilities/Multiview" "MyAppGuide.amigaguide"

Adding the command and the arguments as a single string (e.g. "C:More Readme.txt") will not work. Secondly, these commands are not run asynchronously, so the installation script will be paused until the command is finished. Sometimes this may be desirable (e.g. for Readme files), but for others it may not me (e.g. for launching your application). To get around this you can use the Run command, for example:

  "
@ENDNODE
@NODE "renamestep" "InstallerGen - Rename Step Type"

Rename Step Type

This step type renames a file or drawer. A message can be included to let the user know what's happening.

The Item to Rename field contains the file or drawer to be renamed, and can be a variable or a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "Env:MyEnvFile".

The New Name field contains the name to be renamed to. Again, a variable or constant string can be used here, so be sure to use quotes for a constant string!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "deletestep" "InstallerGen - Delete Step Type"

Delete Step Type

This step type deletes a file or drawer. A message can be included to let the user know what's happening.

The Item to Delete field contains the file or drawer to be renamed, and can be a variable or a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "T:MyTempFile".

Please be careful with this command - don't delete anything you shouldn't!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "assignstep" "InstallerGen - Assign Step Type"

Assign Step Type

This step type creates an assign directly from the installer script. This can be quite useful if your installation requires an assign, so that the user can use the application right away without having to reboot to activate the assign.

A message can be added to let the user know what's happening.

The Assign Name field contains the name of the assign to create, for example MyProg. Please do not include the trailing semicolon!

The Assign Destination field contains the directory the assign will point to. This will normally be a variable such as @default-dest, but can be a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "SYS:MyDir".

@ENDNODE
@NODE "setstep" "InstallerGen - Set Variable Step Type"

Set Variable Step Type

This step is used to set the contents of a variable.

The Variable Name field contains the variable to set.

The Contents field contains the contents to store in the variable, and can be a variable or a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "MyProgram".

The Contents field can also contain an internal Installer utility command, for example (tackon @default-dest "Data") for storing the subdirectory of the default destination called Data in the variable.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "catstep" "InstallerGen - Concatenate Strings Step Type"

Concatenate Strings Step Type

This step is used to join two strings and store the result in a variable.

The Variable Name field contains the variable to store the result in.

String 1 and String 2 contain the strings to be joined in that order. These fields can be a variable or a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "MyProgram".

The string fields can also contain an internal Installer utility command, for example (tackon @default-dest "Data") for storing the subdirectory of the default destination called Data in the variable.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "installercommandstep" "InstallerGen - Installer Command Step Type"

Installer Command Step Type

This step is used to insert a standard Installer utility command into the script. The string entered in the Command field is entered in its entirety.

For more information, please read the Installer guide included in the Installer 43.3 distribution, freely available on Aminet.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "versionstep" "InstallerGen - Get Version Step Type"

Get Version Step Type

This step is used to get the version of a file.

The Variable Name field contains the variable to set with the version details.

The Filename field contains the file to be checked, and can be a variable or a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "LIBS:commodities.library".

Please not that if the file does not exist, this function will return the value 0 so please check also that the file @{"exists" LINK "existsstep"}!

The result is a 32-bit integer, with the high 16-bit word representing the version part (for example the 45 in 45.2) and the low 16-bit word representing the revision part (the 2 in 45.2). To separate these numbers, some extra calculations can be carried out. This can be done by entering the calculation in a @{"Set step" LINK "setstep"}.

To get just the version number, use the calculation (/ #vernum 65536)

To get just the version number, use the calculation (/ #vernum 65536)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "existsstep" "InstallerGen - Checks Exitst Step Type"

Check Exists Step Type

This step is used to check if a file or drawer exists.

The Variable Name field contains the variable to store the result.

The Filename field contains the file or drawer to be checked, and can be a variable or a constant string. Be sure to use quotes when entering a constant string, for example "LIBS:commodities.library".

The result stored in hte variable will be 0 if the filename doesn't exist, 1 if it exists and is a file, and 2 if it exists and is a directory.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "exitstep" "InstallerGen - Exit Step Type"

Exit Step Type

This step is used to make the Installer utility stop execution and exit the script prematurely. This could be used for example to exit the installer before installation if a particular version of a library isn't found.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "optionswindow" "InstallerGen - Options Window"

InstallerGen Options Window

This is the window that opens when the Open List... gadget is clicked for file copying or multiple choice steps. Entries can be created, moved and deleted in the list as they are in the main step list by using the gadgets below the list.

For file copying steps, the list contains the source file or drawer in the first column, the destination path in the second column, and the type of entry (file or drawer) in the third column. An extra gadget is included for adding drawers to the list. Adding drawers is also possible using the Add button under the list but care must be taken to ensure the path is as expected.

For multiple choice steps, the list contains the available options in the first column, the variable assigned to that option in the second column, and whether or not the option is enabled by default in the third column. The Active Entry checkbox is used to set an entry as enabled by default.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "varswindow" "InstallerGen - Variables Window"

InstallerGen Variables Window

This window can be opened using the Script->Show Variables... menu item of the main window, or by clicking the "?" button beside the Variable field in the Step Controls pane. It lists all the variables currently used in the project.

The left column shows the variable names, and the right shows the first step that variable is used in. Some variables are available from the start without having to be used in any steps. These will have "N/A" in the step column.

Double-clicking on an entry in the list will copy the variable name to the clipboard so that it can easily be pasted into any text gadget as needed.

The variables list is only refreshed when the window is opened, so to refresh the list, close the window and then reopen it.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "warningswindow" "InstallerGen - Warnings Window"

InstallerGen Warnings Window

This window shows a list of all the warnings encountered the last time an install script was generated. It will open automatically when a warning is encountered during generation, or by using the menu item Script->Show Warnings...

The list of warnings shows the step number the warning occurred on in the first column, the level on the warning in the second column (1=information / advice, 5=minor, 10=major), roughly in line with AmigaDOS error levels. The description tells you about the warning in the third column.

Clicking on a warning in this list will select the corresponding step in the main list.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "example" "InstallerGen - The Example Project"

The Example Project

Included in the archive is a file called "InstallerGen Project". This is the actual project file I used to create the Install InstallerGen script, and I included it in the archive as an example of how to make a simple script. It contains 8 steps as follows:

 @{b}- 1: Welcome step@{ub}
This step overrides the default welcome message with a custom one.

 @{b}- 2: Choose installation location@{ub}
This step gives a message to the user asking them to select a location for installation. The "Create drawer automatically" option is selected, so the script will create an InstallerGen drawer during the file copying. The user's selected path is saved to the @default-dest variable, which is the recommended variable name for the installation location. The script will append the drawer name (InstallerGen in this case) to this path as the destination. Basic help is included but the default might be better here!

 @{b}- 3: Copy the files@{ub}
This step copies the necessary files over to the new location. Icons are copied over automatically when the "Create / copy / delete icons automatically" option is enabled so they don't necessarily have to be included in the list. Force confirmation is off so the user doesn't get the option to select files - it just goes ahead and copies them.
Opening the list shows the files to be copied. All the files have a blank destination as these will be copied into the destination drawer itself. The Icons/ drawer has Icons as the destination so that its contents are copied into the subdirectory Icons at the destination.

 @{b}- 4: User options@{ub}
This step gives the user a couple of checkboxes that they can enable or disable. The resulting bitmask is stored in #options. The options allow the user to choose to open the readme file and the InstallerGen application. The individual results for these options are stored in the variables #openapp and #readme respectively. Opening the list shows the options, and shows that the option to open the readme file is enabled by default.

 @{b}- 5: Open Readme?@{ub}
This step is an 'if' statement. It checks if the variable #readme is equal to 1 (selected).

 @{b}- 6: Opening Readme@{ub}
This step opens the readme file using the Run Command step type. It has the option "Link to previous 'If' statement" option enabled, which means it is only executed if the previous 'If' statement (in this case step 5) is true. The command uses Multiview to open the readme and supplies the readme file as a second constant string. The installer then waits at this step until the readme is closed.

 @{b}- 7: Open InstallerGen?@{ub}
This is a second 'if' statement. It checks if the variable #openapp is equal to 1 (selected). This step also has the "Link to previous 'If' statement" option disabled, which stops the previous 'If' statement and is therefore executed every time, regardless of the results of the previous 'If' statement.

 @{b}- 8: Run InstallerGen Asynchronously@{ub}
The final step runs InstallerGen, but only if the previous 'If' statement (step 7) was found to be true. It runs it asynchronously by using the standard "Run" command, and providing InstallerGen as the second argument string.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "variables" "InstallerGen - Variables"

InstallerGen Variables

The Installation utility uses variables in its script. It has very loose rules regarding variable names, however there are some recommendations and conventions you should bear in mind when creating your scripts.

Internal variables are signified by starting with an "@" symbol. These have specific meanings, some of which are very useful. For example, @default-dest is the variable that stores the path to the installation location. This should always be set to the actual installation location.

Other standard variables include @app-name which stores the name of the package being installed, @user-level which stores the user's selection for experience level at the start of installation, and @installer-version which contains the version number of the Installer utility.

User-defined variables can be called pretty much anything that isn't an Installer utility keyword. However, the official guidelines recommend prepending a "#" symbol to custom variable names to prevent clashes with existing keywords, or keywords possibly introduced in future versions of the Installer utility. For example, use #MyFolder instead of MyFolder.

Also, avoid using variables beginning with "P_" as this is reserved for the names of internal procedures.

String constants can be used in most cases where a variable name is expected. To do this, simply enter quotes at each end of the string, for example "SYS:Prefs". Internal Installer commands and evaluations can also be entered once enclosed in their parenthesis, for example (tackon @default-dest "Data"). Please note that these statements can get quite complex and so you should really have a grasp of the Installer language to avoid problems.

For more information, please read the Installer guide included in the Installer 43.3 distribution, freely available on Aminet.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "limitations" "InstallerGen - Bugs and Limitations"

Bugs and Limitations of InstallerGen

InstallerGen has some limitations as follows:

 - While or ForEach steps are not currently supported.

 - Nested If statements are all cancelled together at the first unlinked step.

 - Inserting variables mixed with strings is not directly supported, requiring the use of a (cat) command or manually editing the script afterwards.

 - Installer scripts cannot be imported as projects.

 - Adding assigns with spaces in the target path names won't work properly.

 - Projects aren't loaded when given as an argument, either through Workbench or the CLI. This means using InstallerGen as the default tool for a project will start InstallerGen but will not load the project.


Some of these limitations may be addressed in a later version.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "future" "InstallerGen - Future"

InstallerGen - Future

InstallerGen works quite well as it is (on my machines anyway!), but there are some limitations and in general is only really for relatively straightforward scripts. Nevertheless I'm sure there are a few things which could be done to improve it in the future.

For a start, there are more step types I'd like to add or improve, for example steps to rename files during copying, looping steps, executing AmigaDOS commands and so on.

I also might consider support for autoinstall scripts to allow compatibility with AmiUpdate's autoinstall feature.

Feel free to @{"contact me" Link "aboutme"} if you have any suggestions for future versions of InstallerGen!

@ENDNODE
